Here's the full setup:

**AppShell.xaml**

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<Shell x:Class="MyApp.AppShell"
       xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
       xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
       xmlns:views="clr-namespace:MyApp.Views"
       FlyoutBehavior="Flyout"
       Title="MyApp">

    <!-- Dashboard: single page, no tabs -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Dashboard" Icon="icon_dashboard.png">
        <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:DashboardPage}" />
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Products: two tabs -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Products" Icon="icon_products.png">
        <Tab Title="Active">
            <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ActiveProductsPage}" />
        </Tab>
        <Tab Title="Archived">
            <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ArchivedProductsPage}" />
        </Tab>
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Settings -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Settings" Icon="icon_settings.png">
        <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:SettingsPage}" />
    </FlyoutItem>

</Shell>
```

**AppShell.xaml.cs**

```csharp
namespace MyApp;

public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Register the route so you can navigate with:
        //   await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage));
        // or with a parameter:
        //   await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?id={product.Id}");
        Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(Views.ProductDetailsPage), typeof(Views.ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`FlyoutItem`** = top-level flyout entry. Wrapping `ShellContent` directly (Dashboard/Settings) gives a single page with no tab bar.
- **`Tab`** inside a `FlyoutItem` creates a bottom tab bar — here "Active" and "Archived" appear as tabs under Products.
- **`ContentTemplate` with `DataTemplate`** — pages are lazily created only when navigated to.
- **`Routing.RegisterRoute`** registers `ProductDetailsPage` as a non-visible route you push onto the navigation stack programmatically. It won't appear in the flyout.

To receive the `id` query parameter in `ProductDetailsPage`, decorate it with `[QueryProperty]`:

```csharp
[QueryProperty(nameof(ProductId), "id")]
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public string ProductId { get; set; }
    // ...
}
```
